Introduction

The following research aims to explore plaquing patterns in SPb and analyze commemorative strategies of the city authorities.

Step 1. Gathering, cleaning and ingesting the data

Parsing the data

The most extensive but not nearly exhaustive repository of information on memorial plaques of Saint Petersburg can be found in Encyclopedia of Saint Petersburg website with 887 pages of plaques devoted to individuals. If we refer to the website , well se that theres 30 pages that we will nedd to go through. To do so we will need to perform this chunk of code:

plaques_web <- xml2::read_html('http://encspb.ru/object/2805516545/D_1803401815/')

plaque_object_inventory <- c()

for( i in 1:30 ) {
    url_to_query <- paste0("http://encspb.ru/object/2805516545/D_1803401815/", i)
    page_content <- httr::GET(url_to_query)
    page_dom <- xml2::read_html(page_content$content)
    plaque_objects <- xml_attr(xml2::xml_find_all(page_dom, "//a[@class='wp_td_link link']"), "href")
    plaque_object_inventory <- c(plaque_object_inventory, plaque_objects)
}

Next step is to get all the files with the individual plaque pages. It will make the following extracton of the information faster. Im also storing the unique IDs of every page, for thevariable that will come in handy in the future.

html_list <- c()
ids <- c()

for(obj in plaque_object_inventory) {
  
    url_to_query <- paste0("http://encspb.ru", obj)

    # Unique ID
    objid <- gsub('[^0-9.-]','', obj)
    ids <- c(ids, objid)

    curr_html_name <- paste0("plaques_file", objid, ".html")
    html_list <- c(html_list, curr_html_name)
    
    # httr::GET(url_to_query,
    #           write_disk(curr_html_name))
}

And further on, the following chunk of code will go through the files and extract the information on the name of the plaqued person(title), text inscripred on plaque, the year of plaque installation and address. As the website is fairly old and rather disorganized, I will copy the whole plaque related text into one extra variable called description for backup. If extracting information with following-sibling method turns out to be inefficient, I will be able to simply split description column into three.

plaque_address <- c()
plaque_title <- c()
plaque_content <-  c()
plaque_year <- c()

for (n in html_list) {

  page_content <- read_file(n)
  curr_page <- xml2::read_html(page_content)
  
#column with name(title)
  page_title <- html_nodes(curr_page, "h3")
  pl_title <- html_text(page_title)
  
  if (length(pl_title) == 0) {
    pl_title <- NA
  }
  
  plaque_title <- c(plaque_title, pl_title)
  
#column with year, architect, material
  pl_year <- xml2::xml_find_all(curr_page, "//div[@class='inner_object']/text()[preceding-sibling::br[3]][1]")
  pl_year <- xml_text(pl_year)
  
  if (length(pl_year) == 0) {
    pl_year <- NA
  }
  plaque_year <-  c(plaque_year, pl_year)

  
#column with description
  page_desc <- html_nodes(curr_page, ".inner_object")
  pl_description <- html_text(page_desc)
  pl_content <- gsub('\n', '', pl_description)
  pl_content <- gsub( '\\s+', ' ', pl_content)

  if (length(pl_content) == 0) {
    pl_content <- NA
  }
  
  plaque_content <- append(plaque_content, pl_content)
  
#column with address
  pl_address <- xml2::xml_find_all(curr_page, "//div[@class='grName']/following-sibling::a[3]")
  pl_address <- xml_text(pl_address[1])
  
  if (length(pl_address) == 0) {
    pl_address <- NA
  }
  
  plaque_address <- c(plaque_address, pl_address[1])
  
}

Finally, the dataset can be created.

df_plaques <-  data.frame(
  ID = ids,
  TITLE = plaque_title,
  DESCRIPTION = plaque_content,
  ARCHITECT = plaque_year,
  ADDRESS = plaque_address)

As feared, following-sibling method did not work out. Unfortunatelly it resulted in numerous mistakes in the dataset. So, trying to separate the description column into Text, Year, Material, Presence of sculptor and Address seems to be a reasonable solution. But first, lets look at the descriprion of some of the plaques and figure the anchors that could be used as separators.

## [1] "  ..,    /  /       19821983        1992. .  . . . ., 1 (-143)      . .   ./-, . 1 "                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             
## [2] "  . . [  ,     ],    /  /   ,        ,  1850  1860 .      ,   :  . . [ - .  (.)],  .., - ..,  .. [ - . .(.)],  ..1997. .  . .,   . . .. ,  , 1.  -  . (-2)   . .  . .  . .  .. -     ./ ., . 1   -   (. ,  ., 1) "
## [3] "  . .,    /  /         1925  1936      1989. .  . . . ., 29,  ,        . .   ./-, . 29      . "

For extrcting plaque text its possible to use quotation marks as a separator. For address separation seems to be a perfect solution to get rid of the part thats goes before the address and for after part. Then

#description
new_df <- df_plaques %>% separate(DESCRIPTION, c("Trash", "Description", "Other"), sep = "([\\\\])") %>%
  select (-Trash)

#person
new_df <- new_df %>% separate(TITLE, c("Person", "z"), sep = ",") %>% select(-z)
new_df <- new_df %>% separate(Person, c("Person", "z"), sep = "\\[") %>% select(-z)

#address
new_df <- new_df %>% separate(Other, c("Other", "Address"), sep = "")
new_df <- new_df %>% separate(Address, c("Address", "q"), sep = "") %>% select(-q) 

#creators
new_df <- new_df %>% separate(Other, c("Other", "Architect"), sep = ".")

#year
new_df <- new_df %>% separate(Other, c("Year", "Other"), sep = ". ", extra = "merge")

#storing sculptor and material in a variable that I'll need later
plaques <- new_df %>% unite("Other", Other:Architect, remove = TRUE) %>%
  select(-c("ADDRESS", "ARCHITECT"))

Geo-encoding

pl_longitude <- c()
pl_latitude <-  c()

register_google(key = "AIzaSyApbGcAM8vQ13zp-sZUm0skQjRBWwCdVe8")

for (row in 1:nrow(plaques)) {
  curr_addr <- plaques[row, "Address"]
  
  if (!is.na(curr_addr)) {
    rawgeo <- geocode(as.character(curr_addr, output='all'))
    curr_long <- format(rawgeo$results[[1]]$geometry$location$lng, digits=20)
    curr_lat <- format(rawgeo$results[[1]]$geometry$location$lat, digits=20)
    pl_longitude <- c(pl_longitude, curr_long)
    pl_latitude <-  c(pl_latitude, curr_lat)
  }
  else {
    pl_longitude <- c(pl_longitude, NA)
    pl_latitude <- c(pl_latitude, NA)
  }
}

Binding datasets

Adding 19 plaques of Alexander II

One of the cases wasnt copied properly from the website, because the page incorporated the data on 19 different plaques, placed inside and outside of the Savior on the Spilled Blood, that described the achievements of Alexander II. So, I will manually create the dataset and merge it with the main plaques data.

id <- 2805524710
person <- " II"
description <- "some text"
year <- "1907"
address <- ".  ./-, . 2, . "
alex_pl_longitude <- "30.3289"
alex_pl_latitude <- "59.9401"
material <- ""
is_sculptor <- "FALSE"

for (i in 1:18) {
  id <- c(id, paste0("2805524710", i))
  person <- c(person, " II")
  description <- "some text"
  year <- c(year, "1907")
  address <- c(address, ".  ./-, . 2, . ")
  alex_pl_longitude <- c(alex_pl_longitude, 30.3289)
  alex_pl_latitude <- c(alex_pl_latitude, 59.9401)
  material <- c(material, "")
  is_sculptor <- c(is_sculptor, FALSE)
}

alex_df <- data.table(
  ID = id,
  Person = person,
  Description = description,
  Year = year,
  Address = address,
  pl_latitude = alex_pl_latitude,
  pl_longitude = alex_pl_longitude,
  Material = material,
  Is_sculptor = is_sculptor
)

What types of connection are present?

Extracting connections into a variable

new_plaques[, what_did := NA]
new_plaques[, what_did := as.character(what_did)]

for (row in 1:nrow(new_plaques)) {
  if (grepl("\\s+\\s+", new_plaques[row, 'Description'], ignore.case = T)) {
    new_plaques[row, 'what_did'] = "  "
  }
  else if (grepl("||||||||", new_plaques[row, 'Description'], ignore.case = T)) {
    new_plaques[row, 'what_did'] = ""
  }
  else if (grepl("\\s+||||||", new_plaques[row, 'Description'], ignore.case = T)) {
    new_plaques[row, 'what_did'] = ""
  }
  else if (grepl("|\\s+|\\s+\\s+|\\s+||", new_plaques[row, 'Description'], ignore.case = T)) {
    new_plaques[row, 'what_did'] = "  "
  }
  else if (grepl("||| ||| ", new_plaques[row, 'Description'], ignore.case = T)) {
    new_plaques[row, 'what_did'] = ""
  }
  else if (grepl("||", new_plaques[row, 'Description'], ignore.case = T)) {
    new_plaques[row, 'what_did'] = ""
  }
  else if (grepl("|||", new_plaques[row, 'Description'], ignore.case = T)) {
    new_plaques[row, 'what_did'] = ""
  }
  else if (grepl("|||||||
                 |\\s+|\\s+|", new_plaques[row, 'Description'], ignore.case = T)) {
    new_plaques[row, 'what_did'] = ""
  }
  else if (grepl("||||", new_plaques[row, 'Description'], ignore.case = T)) {
    new_plaques[row, 'what_did'] = ""
  }
  else if (grepl("|||\\s+\\s+|\\s+\\s+|
                 |||//s+||", new_plaques[row, 'Description'], ignore.case = T)) {
    new_plaques[row, 'what_did'] = ""
  }
  else if (grepl("||||", new_plaques[row, 'Description'], ignore.case = T)) {
    new_plaques[row, 'what_did'] = ""
  }
  else if (new_plaques[row, 'Person'] == " II") {
    new_plaques[row, 'what_did'] = ""
  }
  else
    new_plaques[row, 'what_did'] = ""
}

#Merging wikidata

Loading and manipulating the dataset

#removing URL parts
spb_persons_wikidata <- fread("spb_persons_wikidata_raw.csv", encoding = "UTF-8")
spb_persons_wikidata[, human := gsub("http://www.wikidata.org/entity/", "", human, fixed = T)]

#filtering dataset
#by bearth/death date
spb_persons <- spb_persons_wikidata[spb_persons_wikidata[,birthdate < "1940-01-01"]]
spb_persons <- spb_persons_wikidata[spb_persons_wikidata[,deathdate < "1999-01-01"]]
#removing non cyrillic names
spb_persons <- spb_persons[spb_persons[, ! grepl("\\d", humanLabel)]]
spb_persons <- spb_persons[spb_persons[, grepl("[]", humanLabel, ignore.case = T)]]

  }
}

##Analysing plaquing patterns based on time period

new_plaques[, Pl_Period := "unknown period"]
new_plaques[, Pl_y := as.numeric(stri_extract_last_regex(Year, "\\d{4}"))]
for (row in 1:nrow(new_plaques)) {
  if (is.na(new_plaques[row, 'Pl_y'])) {
    new_plaques[row, 'Pl_Period'] <- "Unknown period"
  }
  else if (new_plaques[row, 'Pl_y'] < 1918) {
    new_plaques[row, 'Pl_Period'] <- "1. Empire"
  }
  else if (new_plaques[row, 'Pl_y'] >= 1918 && new_plaques[row, 'Pl_y'] < 1928){
    new_plaques[row, 'Pl_Period'] <- "2. Early soviet"
  }
  else if (new_plaques[row, 'Pl_y'] >= 1928 && new_plaques[row, 'Pl_y'] <= 1953){
    new_plaques[row, 'Pl_Period'] <- "3. Stalin time"
  }
  else if (new_plaques[row, 'Pl_y'] > 1953 && new_plaques[row, 'Pl_y'] <= 1964) {
    new_plaques[row, 'Pl_Period'] <- "4. Ottepel"
  }
  else if (new_plaques[row, 'Pl_y'] > 1964 && new_plaques[row, 'Pl_y'] < 1985) {
    new_plaques[row, 'Pl_Period'] <- "5. Zastoi"
  }
  else if (new_plaques[row, 'Pl_y'] >= 1985 && new_plaques[row, 'Pl_y'] <= 1991) {
    new_plaques[row, 'Pl_Period'] <- "6. Perestroika"
  }
  else if (new_plaques[row, 'Pl_y'] > 1991) {
    new_plaques[row, 'Pl_Period'] <- "7. Federation"
  }
}

Analysing resulting data

The following histogtam is showing number and material of plaques in historic periods. Plaques started immerging in the second half of 18th century, when the concept of national state immerged. Brezhnew period showcases the highest number of plaques. It might be connected to the cultural policy of that time, when commemorative practices started playing more important role in period of stagnation and looming ideological crisis. ##Lenin stats The most plaqued individual is Lenin, so it makes sense to look at him moreclosely. Patterns can be found regarding Lenins bith and death dates.

Is there connectionin general between death date and plaque date in death related plaques?
